]], [[Kryvyi Rih Main Station]], [[Maksyma Hor'koho Square]], [[Saksahan]] boat station\n| image_flag             = Banner of Kryvyi Rih.svg\n| flag_alt               = [[Flag of Kryvyi Rih]]\n| image_shield           = Coat of Arms of Kryvyi Rih.svg\n|image_blank_emblem      = Kryvyi Rih Logotype 01.png\n| shield_alt             = [[Coat of Arms of Kryvyi Rih]]\n| motto                  = Life-long city\n| anthem                 = ''[[Anthem of Krivoy Rog]]''\n| mapsize                         = 230px\n| map_caption                     = Location of Kryvyi Rih in Ukraine\n| pushpin_map                     = Ukraine#Europe\n| pushpin_relief                  = 1\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|47|54|31|N|33|20|36|E|region:UA|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name       = {{UKR}}\n| subdivision_type1      = [[Oblasts of Ukraine|Province]]\n| subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Dnipropetrovsk Oblast}}\n| subdivision_type2      = [[Raions of Ukraine|District]]\n| subdivision_name2      = [[File:Flag of Kryvyi Rih Raion.gif|22px|border]] [[Kryvyi Rih Raion|Kryvyi Rih]]\n----\n| subdivision_type4      = Historic [[Governorates of Russia|Governorates]]\n| subdivision_name4      = [[Kherson Governorate|Kherson]]<br />[[Yekaterinoslav Governorate|Yekaterinoslav]]\n| established_title      = Founded\n| established_date       = 1775 ({{years ago|1775}} years ago)\n| established_title1     = Town charter\n| established_date1      = 1860\n| established_title2     = City status\n| established_date2      = 1919\n| seat_type              = Administrative HQ\n| seat                   = Kryvyi Rih City Hall,<br/>Ploshcha (Square) Molodizhna\n| parts_type             = Raions\n| parts_style            = <!-- Use \"list\" (for list), \"coll\" (for collapsed list), \"para\" (for paragraph format). Default is \"list\" if up to 5 items, then-->\n| parts                  = List of 7\n#[[Terny Raion]]\n#[[Pokrovskyi Raion (Kryvyi Rih)|Pokrovskyi Raion]]\n#[[Saksahan Raion]]\n#[[Central City Raion]]\n#[[Dovhuntsevsky Raion]]\n#[[Metalurhiynyi Raion]]\n#[[Inhulets Raion]]\n| government_type        = [[City council]], [[city of regional significance (Ukraine)|regional]]\n| government_footnotes   = \n| leader_party           = \n| leader_title           = Governing&nbsp;body\n| leader_name            = [[Kryvyi Rih City Council]]\n| leader_title1          = Mayor\n| leader_name1           =  [[Yuriy Vilkul]]<ref>{{in lang|uk}} [http://pda.pravda.com.ua/news/id_7103935/ VILKUL oath mayor of Kryviy Rih], [[Ukrayinska Pravda]] (31 March 2016)</ref>\n| leader_title2          = [[People's Deputy of Ukraine|MPs]]:\n| leader_name2           = Yuri Pavlov <br />Andriy Halchenko<br />Konstantin Usov [[Petro Poroshenko Bloc|(PPB)]]\n| unit_pref              = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes         = \n| area_total_km2         = 430\n| area_land_km2          = \n| area_water_km2         = \n| area_water_percent     = \n| area_note              = \n| elevation_footnotes    = <ref>{{cite web|title= Kryvyi Rih (Ternopil Oblast, Kryvyi Rih Raion)|url=http://weather.in.ua/en/dnepropetrovskaja/12267|work=weather.in.ua|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref>\n| elevation_m            = 84\n| population_footnotes   = \n| population_total       = 629,695\n| population_as_of       = 2018 est.\n| population_rank        = 7th, UA\n| population_density_km2 = auto\n| population_note        = \n| population_metro      = 1,010,000\n| population_demonym     = Kryvorizhanyn, Kryvorizhanka, Kryvorizhtsi\n| timezone               = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n| utc_offset             = +2\n| timezone_DST           = [[EEST]]\n| utc_offset_DST         = +3\n| postal_code_type       = [[Postal code]]\n| postal_code            = 50000-50479\n| area_code_type         = [[Telephone numbering plan|Area code]]\n| area_code              = +380 56(4)\n| website                = {{URL|https://kr.gov.ua/}}\n}}\n\n'''Kryvyi Rih''' ({{lang-uk|\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0301\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433 {{IPA-uk|kr\u026a\u02ccw\u026aj \u02c8r\u207d\u02b2\u207ei\u0266|}}|lit=Crooked Horn}} or 'Curved Cape')<ref>Oxford Dictionaries. \"[http://www.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/english/Kryvyi-Rih?q=Kryvyi+Rih Kryvyi Rih]\". Oxford University Press, 2013. Accessed 27 August 2013.</ref> or '''Krivoy Rog''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0433}} {{IPA-ru|kr\u02b2\u026a\u02ccvoj \u02c8rok|}}) is a city in the [[Dnipropetrovsk Oblast]] of [[Ukraine]]; it is the [[List of cities in Ukraine|7th]]-most populous city in the country.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/zagalna_informatsiya/demografichna_situatsiya |title= UA population estimates |publisher= Office for National Statistics |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20141102004146/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/zagalna_informatsiya/demografichna_situatsiya |archive-date= 2014-11-02 |url-status= dead }}</ref> It lies within a large [[Kryvyi Rih Metropolitan Region|urban area]], administratively incorporated with [[Kryvyi Rih Municipality]] as a [[city of regional significance (Ukraine)|city of regional significance]]. It also serves as the administrative center of the [[Kryvyi Rih Raion|district]], although it is not part of it. \n\nLocated at the confluence of the [[Saksahan]] and [[Inhulets river|Inhulets]] rivers, Kryvyi Rih has been a major settlement for most of its history. It was founded as a postal city in 1775 by the [[Zaporozhian Cossacks|Cossacks]]. Developed as a [[military settlement]] until 1860, it formed part of [[Kherson Governorate]]. It was incorporated during the 20th century with areas of [[Yekaterinoslav Governorate|Yekaterinoslav]]. The [[township]] began to expand \"at an astonishing rate\" at the beginning of the 1880s. Kryvyi Rih's [[urbanization]] was unplanned and stimulated by mining exploitation. [[France|French]] and [[UK|English]] [[investment]] contributed to a boom in [[metallurgy]], [[iron mining]], and investigation of [[Kryvbas|rich deposits of iron ore]]. The [[Yekateryninska Railway]] was built in 1884 to transport iron ore to the [[Donbas]]. This catalyzed the growth of Kryvyi Rih into a major industrial town; it gained [[city]] status in 1919.\n\n[[Nationalization]] and investment spurred by [[1917 Revolution|Soviet authorities]] led to extensive growth. In 1934 [[Kryvorizhstal]] was built, the first of more than 500 factories. [[Kryvyi Rih National University]] was founded here. Financially, the city's postwar growth after the [[Second World War|Nazi]] occupation increased after 1965 due to [[1965 Soviet economic reform|economic reforms]]. Also, investment spurred by [[Declaration of Independence of Ukraine|Ukrainian Independence]], institution of a [[market economy]] led to extensive regeneration, particularly in the city centre.\n\n{{As of | 2016}} Kryvyi Rih is arguably the main [[steel industry|steel-industry]] city of [[Eastern Europe]]. It is a large, globally important centre of the [[iron-ore]] [[mining]] and [[metallurgy]] region, known as the [[Kryvbas]]. The economy of the [[Oblasts of Ukraine|oblast]] is the second-largest in Ukraine (after [[Kiev]]).<ref>\n[https://www.rbc.ua/rus/news/gosstat-obnarodoval-dannye-dole-regionov-1553868313.html]\n</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Etymology===\nThe city was founded in the 18th century by [[Zaporozhian Cossacks]]. Kryvyi Rih in Ukrainian literally means \"Crooked [[Horn (anatomy)|Horn]]\" or \"Curved Bend\". According to local [[legend]], the city was founded by a \"crooked\" ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] slang for one-eyed) Cossack named ''Rih''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/ru/st/pg/241109205040551_s/ |title=\u041a\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0412.\u041e. I\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440i\u044f \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440i\u0436\u0436\u044f  \u0414\u043d\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a: \u0421i\u0447, 1992 |publisher=kryvyirih.dp.ua |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129034519/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/ru/st/pg/241109205040551_s/ |archive-date=2014-11-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> But, records pre-dating the founding of the city refer to the area by the same name. It appears based on the shape of the landmass formed by the [[confluence]] of the river [[Saksahan]] with the [[Inhulets]].\n\n===Early history===\nThe Ingulets Palanka (an administrative division of the [[Zaporizhian Sich]], a polity of the Cossacks) was established in 1734. A list of villages and winter camps from that time mentions Kryvyi Rih. In 1770<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1734_1900 |title=\u0406\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0445\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0456\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0456\u0439 1734-1900. \u041e\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041e.\u041c\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u043a, \u0432\u0435\u0434\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u043f\u0456\u0432\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0456\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0437\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043e-\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0454\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0447\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u044e |publisher=kryvyirih.dp.ua |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102011503/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1734_1900 |archive-date=2014-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the camp of [[Zaporizhian Sich]] was founded.<ref>\u0412. \u0406\u0437\u043c\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432. \u041f\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436 \u0443 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0443 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0456\u044e \u0432 1799 \u0440. \u0443 \u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0445, \u0432\u0438\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u043c \u0406\u0437\u043c\u0430\u0439\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043c</ref> Four years later [[Johann Anton G\u00fcldenst\u00e4dt]] visited the area and made the first survey and [[scientific description]].\n\nOn May 8, 1775, after the end of the [[Russian-Turkish War]], [[Russian Empire|Russian authorities]] opened a postal station and railway track, linking this settlement to [[Kremenchuk]], [[Kinburn foreland]] and [[Ochakov]], all garrisons of the [[Imperial Russian Army]]. The station was tended by five Cossacks.\n\nKryvyi Rih was still a [[village]] in the early 1800s.<ref>\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0456\u043a (\u0421\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443) \u043a\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0449 \u0425\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0439 \u041e\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0442\u0456\u0432, \u044f\u043a\u0456 \u0443 1816 - 1817 \u0440.\u0440. \u0431\u0443\u043b\u0438 \u0437\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0456 \u0443 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0456 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f</ref> It had three [[water mill]]s, which made up the largest industry. The first stone houses were built in 1828.<ref>\u00ab\u041f\u043e \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456\u0439 \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0456\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0456\u00bb, \u0432\u0438\u043f. 1-\u0439, Katerinoslaw, 1903 \u0440</ref> The village became a [[township]] in 1860.<ref name=\"encdict\"/>\n\n[[File:Synagogue of kryvyi Rih.jpg|thumb|left|Synagogue of Kryvyi Rih, 19th century]]\nThe tallest building at the end of the 1800s was the Central Synagogue, built by the thriving Jewish community. They worked as artisans, traders and merchants.<ref name=\"encdict\">''Brockhaus and Efron Encyclopedic Dictionary 1890\u20141907''</ref>\n\n===Industrial growth===\n[[Alexander Pol]] (also known as Paul), a Ukrainian geologist, discovered and initiated iron ore investigation and production in this area. He is credited with discovering the [[Kryvbas]].<ref>Sudrussland Mageteisen und Sisenglantztatten</ref><ref>\u0420\u0443\u0431\u0456\u043d \u041f.\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0435\u0439\u043d \u0438 \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0440\u0443\u0434\u044b. \u0413\u043e\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b, 1888 \u0433., \u0442. 1</ref> This stimulated formation of a mining district.<ref>\u041a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u043a\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0421. \u0413\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441 \u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0446\u044c \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0420\u043e\u0433\u0443, \u0425\u0435\u0440\u0441\u043e\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0457 \u0433\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0456\u0457</ref> In 1874 [[Alexander II of Russia|Alexander II]] initiated a railway,<ref>\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d-\u043b\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u043c\u0435\u0447\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430\u00bb, \u0412\u0438\u0434. \u041e\u0431-\u0432\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0438\u043d\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0432, 1900 \u0440</ref> to run 505&nbsp;km. This enabled transportation connecting to the nearest factories and greatly sped up the development of the region.\n\nIn 1880, with 5 million [[franc]]s of [[Capital (economics)|capital]], Paul founded the \"French Society of Kryvyi Rih Ores\". In 1882 16.4 thousand tons of ore were extracted from surface mines on the outskirts of town by 150 workers. A centre of capitalism, this region was the greatest area of ore extraction in the Russian empire. The first underground mine of the basin began operations in 1886.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1734_1900/pochatok_dobutku_zaliznoi_rudi_industrialniy_rozvitok_1881_1899 |title=\u041f\u043e\u0447\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043a \u0434\u043e\u0431\u0443\u0442\u043a\u0443 \u0437\u0430\u043b\u0456\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u0440\u0443\u0434\u0438. \u0406\u043d\u0434\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0456\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u043e\u0437\u0432\u0438\u0442\u043e\u043a (1881 \u2013 1899) |publisher=kryvyirih.dp.ua |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129034539/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1734_1900/pochatok_dobutku_zaliznoi_rudi_industrialniy_rozvitok_1881_1899 |archive-date=2014-11-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Metallurgy, a new branch of industry, was founded in 1892, when the first blast furnace of ''Hdantsivka'' [[ironworks]] was started. The export of ore to [[Silesia]] soon began.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Olexander Paul.jpg|[[Alexander Pol]] studied iron ore in detail and proved its commercial value\nFile:1899 in Kryvyi Rih 10.jpg|Ore quarry in 1899\nFile:Krivoi-Rog Iron Mining Company Stocks 01.JPG|Jolta\u0457a Rieka Iron Mining Company [[Share (finance)|share]], 1899\nFile:Kryvyi Rih Credit Union.jpg|Poshtova Street about 1900\nFile:Kryvyi Rih Pochtovaya Street.jpg|Krivoy Rog Mutual Credit Society\nfile:Kryvyi Rih Region Map 1914.jpg|Region map in 1914\n</gallery>\n\nFive schools were soon established.<ref>\u0414\u0456\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0456 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0446\u0456\u0439\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433. 1914 \u0440</ref> An aerial cableway was built in the town. The city's industry attracted new people looking for a quick profit.<ref>\u0413\u0456\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043e-\u0437\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a \u21164, 1902\u0440</ref> The [[supply (economics)|supply]] of mined ore soon exceeded [[demand]]. Many mines had to temporarily suspend operations, and others had to reduce their workers and output by more than half. Workers had harsh conditions, lacking social security, or contracts. Environmental conditions in the mines caused them to suffer lung cancer, [[tuberculosis]] and [[asthma]]. The shutdown caused thousands of people to be out of work. At the same time, workers began to develop ideas about socialism and democracy. The labor unrest resulted in several terrorist attacks and [[Strike action|strikes]]. In 1905 there were also anti-Jewish [[pogroms]] and repressions, and younger Jews left the area, many for the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1900_1917/1900_1903 |title=\u0406\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0445\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0456\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0456\u0439 (\u043c. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433) 1900-1903 |publisher=kryvyirih.dp.ua |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129034536/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1900_1917/1900_1903 |archive-date=2014-11-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[First World War]] interrupted access to the export markets, and many workers were drafted into the military. The city survived [[Soldier and Worker's Deputies]] in 1917.<!-- What is this? --> Soviet power was established in January 1918.<ref name=\"kryvyirih.dp.ua\">{{cite web|url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1917_2002/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1919_1921|title=\u0406\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0445\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0456\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0456\u0439 (\u043c. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433) 1900-1903|publisher=kryvyirih.dp.ua|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129034531/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1917_2002/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1919_1921|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>\u0421\u043d\u0435\u0433\u0438\u0440\u0451\u0432 \u0412. \u0412. \u041c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443 \u0434\u0432\u0443\u0445 \u043e\u0433\u043d\u0435\u0439. \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u044b\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0414\u041a\u0420 // \u00ab\u041c\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0433\u0432\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0435\u0446\u00bb \u2014 \u041b\u0443\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a, 6\u221211.10.1990.</ref>\n\nThe [[Donetsk\u2013Krivoy Rog Soviet Republic]],<ref>\u041c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044b \u043e \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e-\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0435. \u0421\u043e\u0441\u0442. \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0441\u043b. \u0425. \u041c\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0438\u0441 // \u00ab\u041b\u0456\u0442\u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441 \u0420\u0435\u0432\u043e\u043b\u044e\u0446\u0456\u0457\u00bb: \u0416\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b \u0406\u0441\u0442\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0443 \u0426\u041a \u041a\u041f(\u0431)\u0423 \u2014 1928. \u2014 \u2116 3(30).</ref> founded on 12 February 1918, became a self-declared republic of the Russian SFSR and sought independence from Ukraine. On 29 March 1918 it became a republic within Ukraine, but was fully occupied by German forces in support of the [[Central Rada]]. It was disbanded on 20 March 1918<ref>\u0413\u0430\u043c\u0440\u0435\u0446\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u042e. \u041c. \u0406\u0406 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0437\"\u0457\u0437\u0434 \u0420\u0430\u0434 \u0420\u043e\u0431\u0456\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0438\u0445 \u0456 \u0421\u043e\u043b\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0414\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0456\u0432 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0443 \u0456 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0436\u0436\u044f // \u041f\u0438\u0442\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0457 \u0421\u0420\u0421\u0420, \u2116 22. \u2014 \u0425\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0456\u0432, 1977.</ref> when the independence of Soviet Ukraine was announced.<ref>\u041b\u0438\u0445\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0442 \u0410. \u0412. \u0417\u0434\u0456\u0439\u0441\u043d\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043b\u0435\u043d\u0456\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0457 \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0456\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0456\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0456 \u2014 \u041a\u0438\u0457\u0432, 1967. \u2014 \u0421.156\u2212161.</ref>\n\nAround this time, Kryvyi Rih's status was changed from township to city. It was founded by [[Uyezd]] as part of the [[Yekaterinoslav Governorate]]. It included 30 [[volost]]s. In late 1919, it was briefly ruled by the [[Volunteer Army]].<ref name=\"kryvyirih.dp.ua\"/>\n\n===Soviet era===\nOn January 17, 1920 the Red Army finally took Kryvyi Rih. The city's population totaled 22,571. The city did not have a drinking water system until 1924, when a 55.3&nbsp;km (34.4&nbsp;mi) system was laid underground. Foreign investments were stopped, and the mine operations were revived. The first [[Kryvyi Rih National University|Mining Institute]] opened in 1929. The Medical and [[Kryvyi Rih Pedagogical Institute|Pedagogical Institutes]] were founded.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://knu.edu.ua/zagalna-informatsiia/istoriia-knu#.VG4Mf4usV8E |title=\u0406\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0456\u044f \u041a\u041d\u0423 |publisher=knu.edu.ua |accessdate= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150322110014/http://knu.edu.ua/zagalna-informatsiia/istoriia-knu#.VG4Mf4usV8E |archive-date=2015-03-22 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1931 the foundation of the [[Kryvorizhstal|metallurgical works]] was laid.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arcelormittal.com.ua/|title=Our History. ArcelorMittal. |publisher=arcelormittal.com.ua|accessdate=}}</ref> The first blast furnace of the metallurgical works produced steel three years later. The city grew rapidly. In 2002 it had 160 industrial enterprises and 947 shops.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{cite web|url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1917_2002|title=\u0406\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0445\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0456\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0456\u0439 1917 - 2002|publisher=kryvyirih.dp.ua|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129034525/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok/istorichna_khronika_podiy_1917_2002|archive-date=2014-11-29|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Nazi occupation====\nDuring World War II, Kryvyi Rih was occupied by the [[Wehrmacht|German Army]] as part of the [[Reichskommissariat Ukraine]] from August 15, 1941 to February 22, 1944. From 20 September 1941 to August 1944, the Government, factories, and Kryvyi Rih Institute were evacuated to [[Nizhny Tagil]].\n\nGermans immediately began to build up local government, installing executives, [[gendarmerie]] and police forces. The Ukrainian national liberation movement in Krivoy Rog was organized by marching groups [[OUN]]. The Nazis conducted ethnic cleansing of mostly Jewish residents, in a large-scale [[holocaust]]. On October 13, 1941 the Nazis executed 700 people.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewish-museum-marmer.dp.ua/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2&Itemid=1|title=Marmer Jewish Museum |publisher=jewish-museum-marmer.dp.ua |accessdate=}}</ref> From October 1941 to April 1942, the Nazis killed 6293 persons, in August 1943&nbsp;\u2013 13 people.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/> A total of 5,000 Jews were murdered, and 800 [[POW]]s from a nearby camp. Thousands of Jews had fled the area to the east before the Germans reached the city.\n\nHitler had repeatedly stressed the crucial importance of this area \"The Nikopol manganese is of such importance, it cannot be expressed in words. Loss of Nikopol (on the [[Dnieper River]], southwest of Zaporozhye) would mean the end of war.\"<ref>\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0412\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b. 1939\u20141945. / \u041a\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0438\u0432 \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432. \u2014 \u0422. 8. \u2014 \u041c.: \u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442, 1977.</ref>  The German bridgehead on the left bank of the Dnieper gave the German command a base in order to restore the land connection with their forces locked in the Crimea.<ref>\u0422\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0440\u0445 \u041a. \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0412\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b. \u2014 \u0421\u041f\u0431.: \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0433\u043e\u043d; \u041c.:\u0410\u0421\u0422, 1999.</ref> During the first half of January,<ref>\u0413\u0440\u044b\u043b\u0435\u0432 \u0410. \u041d. \u0414\u043d\u0435\u043f\u0440 \u2014 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u043f\u0430\u0442\u044b \u2014 \u041a\u0440\u044b\u043c. \u2014 \u041c.: \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0430, 1970.</ref> Soviet troops made repeated attempts to eliminate the Nikopol-Krivoy Rog enemy group, but because of the stubborn resistance of German troops, did not achieve success. The fleeing German Army almost totally destroyed Kryvyi Rih during the [[Nikopol\u2013Krivoy Rog Offensive]].\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 102-10648, Entwurf eines Kraftwerks f\u00fcr S\u00fcd-Russland.jpg|[[AEG]] power station built in 1930\nFile:Germans in Kriwoi Rog.jpg|[[Wehrmacht]] soldiers operating [[10.5 cm leFH 18]]. Svobody Street, 1942\nFile:Krivoi Rog WW3.jpg|Soldiers arresting people, 1942\nFile:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-17031-0001, Bergarbeiter, Ehrung.jpg|Miners and [[Pioneer (military)|pioneers]] pose in front of the [[The Banner of Krivoi Rog|Banner of Krivoi Rog]]. 1952.\nFile:Kryvyi Rih8.jpg|Dimitrova Street, like many in the city center, is lined with dozens of [[Stalinist architecture|Stalinist]] buildings\nFile:Kryvyi Rih - building3.jpg|City Hall was built in the year of the city's 200th jubilee.\nFile:Nativity of the Theotokos Church, Kryvyi Rih.jpeg|[[The church of the Nativity of the All-holy Theotokos (Kryvyi Rih)|Nativity of the Theotokos Church]], 1886, restored in the 2000s<ref>\u0411\u043e\u0436\u043a\u043e \u0410. \u0410. \u0425\u0440\u0430\u043c \u0420\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0432\u044f\u0442\u043e\u0439 \u0411\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0446\u044b (1886\u20142012): \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a / \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0435\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u043e\u0436\u043a\u043e. \u2014 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0433, 2012. \u2014 84 \u0441., \u0438\u043b.</ref>\n</gallery>\n\n===Post-Second World War and Post-Soviet===\nAfter the war, people lived among the ruins while rebuilding the housing stock. The housing shortage was met by innovative technological solutions, and temporary barracks and houses were quickly built. The two chief kinds of cheap new materials {{clarify|date=May 2012}} were used later for years afterward.\n[[File:\u0420\u0430\u0434\u0443\u0433\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0436\u0434\u044f.jpg|thumb|Modern Old Town view]]\n\nIn the late 1940s, initiatives such as [[Stakhanovite movement]] stimulated redevelopment:<ref>\u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0434\u044f\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0435\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0456\u044f. \u0412 12-\u0442\u0438 \u0442\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0445 / \u0417\u0430 \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u041c. \u0411\u0430\u0436\u0430\u043d\u0430. \u2014 2-\u0433\u0435 \u0432\u0438\u0434. \u2014 \u041a.: \u0413\u043e\u043b. \u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043a\u0446\u0456\u044f \u0423\u0420\u0415, 1974-1985.</ref> [[Khrushchyovka]]s, new mines, shoe and wool spinning-factories, the [[Central Iron Ore Enrichment Works]], [[Northern Iron Ore Enrichment Works]], and building the City Circus. [[Trolleybuses in Kryvyi Rih]] were launched in 1957,<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">\u0415\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438: \u0415\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0443\u0442\u0456\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a / \u0421\u0435\u0440\u0433\u0456\u0439 \u0422\u0430\u0440\u0445\u043e\u0432, \u041a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u041a\u043e\u0437\u043b\u043e\u0432, \u0410\u0430\u0440\u0435 \u041e\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0435\u0440. \u2014 \u041a\u0438\u0457\u0432: \u0421\u0438\u0434\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0412. \u0411., 2010. \u2014 912 \u0441.: \u0456\u043b., \u0441\u0445\u0435\u043c\u0438. \u2014 {{ISBN|978-966-2321-11-1}}.</ref>\n\n[[Kryvyi Rih International Airport|Kryvyi Rih Airport]] became International. By 1990 Kryvbas produced 42% of [[USSR]] and 80% of [[Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic|Ukrainian]] ore.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arcelormittal.com.ua/index.php?id63|title=Our History. ArcelorMittal.|publisher=arcelormittal.com.ua|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nSince the late 20th century, large sections of the city dating from the 1960s have been either demolished and re-developed or modernised with the use of beton and steel.<ref>\u041e\u0441\u0443\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u043c \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043e\u0431\u044a\u0435\u043a\u0442\u044b \u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430 \u0418\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0444\u0430 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0430 // \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440 \u0418\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0444 \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0441: \u0421\u0443\u0434\u044c\u0431\u0430 \u0438 \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e (\u0410\u043b\u044c\u0431\u043e\u043c-\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u043a \u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0438\u044e \u0441\u043e \u0434\u043d\u044f \u0440\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f) / \u041f\u043e\u0434 \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u0411\u0430\u0431\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d \u0421. \u0412., \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a \u0414., \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0441 \u0418. \u0418., \u0410. \u041f\u0443\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0432; \u0421\u043e\u0441\u0442. \u0414. \u0411\u0440\u0430\u0436\u043d\u0438\u043a, \u0418. \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0438\u0441, \u0418. \u041d\u0435\u0441\u043c\u0438\u044f\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430. \u2014 \u041a\u0438\u0435\u0432, 2002. \u2014 \u0421. 97. \u2014 102 \u0441. \u2014 (\u041d0(4\u0423\u041a\u0420)6-8). \u2014 {{ISBN|966-95095-8-0}}.</ref> Old flats have been converted into modern apartments. Nine [[microdistrict]]s of 17 and 9-floor [[panel\u00e1k]] apartments have since been developed.\n\nThe Kryvyi Rih TV Mast is a 185m-tall, guyed tubular steel mast, built in 1960. It carries three crossbars on two levels, which run from the mast structure to the guys. All three crossbars are equipped with gangways that carry additional smaller antennas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://1kr.ua/news-3248.html|title=\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0442\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0432\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0430. |publisher=1kr ua |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nThe city was rebuilt with broad avenues lined by wide sidewalks. Tram lines run down the center of the major streets. The sidewalks have been lined with several rows of urban trees, such as lindens and horse chestnuts. Many people live in the 5- to 9-story apartment buildings that are built around large inner courtyards. Many courtyards have also been planted with trees, giving the impression that the city is within a park.\n\nUkraine's declaration of independence in 1991 has been followed by radical changes in every sphere of city life\n.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arcelormittal.com.ua/index.php?id=63|title=Our History. ArcelorMittal.|publisher=arcelormittal.com.ua|accessdate=}}</ref> In the 1990s the city was known for crime (mostly organized gangs from neighbourhood's raiding other neighbourhood's<ref name=\"239914Presidenthometown\">[https://ukrainianweek.com/Society/239914 President\u2019s hometown], The Ukrainian Week (27 January 2020)</ref>)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kri.com.ua/4221-beguny-istorija-glupojj-vojjny.html|title=\"\u0411\u0435\u0433\u0443\u043d\u044b\". \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0433\u043b\u0443\u043f\u043e\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0439\u043d\u044b.|publisher=kri.com.ua|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141219035552/http://kri.com.ua/4221-beguny-istorija-glupojj-vojjny.html|archivedate=2014-12-19}}</ref>, but robberies have been suppressed. Investment followed the 2005 [[privatization]] of [[Kryvorizhstal]] by [[ArcelorMittal]], and was aided further by [[Metinvest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krlife.com.ua/tags/tegi/rekonstruktsiya|title=\u0420\u0435\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u043a\u0446\u0438\u044f. |publisher=KRLife|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nKryvyi Rih's city centre has undergone extensive redevelopment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krlife.com.ua/tags/tegi/prospekt-karla-marksa|title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u0441\u043f\u0435\u043a\u0442 \u041c\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0441\u0430. |publisher=KRLife|accessdate=}}</ref> The city has one of the biggest [[flower clock]]s in Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.rambler.ru/11454967/photos/|title=\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0446\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u044b \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0432 \u041a\u043d\u0438\u0433\u0443 \u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0440\u0434\u043e\u0432.|publisher=Rambler News|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129063524/http://news.rambler.ru/11454967/photos/|archivedate=2014-11-29}}</ref> New and renovated complexes such as [[Auchan]] and The Union have become popular shopping and entertainment destinations. Kryvyi Rih is ranked as among the 30<ref>{{cite web |url=http://focus.ua/ratings/276793 |title=\u0424\u043e\u043a\u0443\u0441 \u043e\u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043b 50 \u043b\u0443\u0447\u0448\u0438\u0445 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0436\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0438 \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0435 |publisher=focus.ua |accessdate= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190513113949/https://focus.ua/ratings/276793/ |archive-date=2019-05-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref> most comfortable cities for living in Ukraine.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Government==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"float:right; font-size:88%; margin-left:1em;\"\n|+ The City of Kryvyi Rih and 7 raions\n| style=\"padding-right:1em;\" | \n#[[Terny Raion]]\n#[[Pokrovskyi Raion]]\n#[[Saksahan Raion]]\n#[[Central City Raion]]\n#[[Dovhuntsevsky Raion]]\n#[[Metalurhiynyi Raion]]\n#[[Inhulets Raion]]\n|[[File:Kryvyi Rih Raions.svg|145px]]\n|}\n{{Main|Kryvyi Rih City Council}}\nThe City of Kryvyi Rih is governed by the [[Kryvyi Rih City Council]]. it is a city municipality that is designated as a separate district within its [[oblast]].\n\nAdministratively, the city is divided into \"raions\" (\"districts\"). Presently, there are 7 raions: Dzerzhinskiy, Central City, Terny, Saksahan, Ingulets, Zhovtnevy and Dovhuntsevsky. Small townships, Avanhard, Horniatske, Ternovaty Kut, Kolomoitsevo and Nowoivanovka were added to the City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/karta_saytu_mistseva_vlada |title=\u0412\u0438\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u043e\u043c \u043c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0457 \u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438. |publisher=kryvyirih.dp.ua |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102005537/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/karta_saytu_mistseva_vlada |archive-date=2014-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOriginally Ingulets povit of [[Novorossiysk Governorate]] was established on lands of Ingulets palanca in 1775 after the destruction of the [[Zaporozhian Sich]]. In 1775/1776 it was part of [[Kherson Governorate]]. In 1783, the povit centre became Kryvyi Rih, and it was renamed to Kryvyi Rih povit. In 1860 Kryvyi Rih got the status of township in [[Kherson Governorate]]. In 1919 township was granted city status in [[Yekaterinoslav Governorate]] and, later, [[Dnipropetrovsk Oblast]]. As a result of the administrative reform in 1923 Kryvyi Rih povit converted to Kryvyi Rih okruga, which in 1930 became an independent administrative\nunit of Ukraine.<ref>\u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 \u0438 \u0432\u0430\u0436\u043d\u0463\u0439\u0448\u0456\u044f \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0456\u044f \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0456\u0438. \u041f\u043e \u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043e\u0431\u0441\u043b\u0463\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0456\u044f, \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0430\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u0443\u0447\u0440\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0456\u044f\u043c\u0438 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0412\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0414\u0463\u043b, \u043f\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0456\u044e \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e \u0421\u043e\u0432\u0463\u0442\u0430. \u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0435 \u0426\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u0433\u043e \u0421\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e \u041a\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u0430. \u0412\u044b\u043f\u0443\u0441\u043a VIII. \u0413\u0443\u0431\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0456\u0438 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0456\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043f\u044b. \u0421\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0442\u041f\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0431\u0443\u0440\u0433\u044a. 1886. \u2014 VI + 157 \u0441.</ref><ref>\u0412\u0441\u0435\u0441\u043e\u044e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f 1926 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430. \u041c.: \u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0426\u0421\u0423 \u0421\u043e\u044e\u0437\u0430 \u0421\u0421\u0420, 1928-29. \u0422\u043e\u043c 10-16. \u0422\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 VI. \u041d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u043e \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443, \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438</ref>\n[[File:Kryvyi Rih Logotype 06.png|thumbnail|100px|left|City logo]]\nKryvyi Rih has three single-mandate [[Electoral district|parliamentary constituencies]] entirely within the city, through which members of parliament (MPs) are elected to represent the city in [[Verkhovna Rada|Rada]]. At the last general election, were won by [[Petro Poroshenko Bloc|PPB]] and independent candidates with representation being from Yuri Pavlov, Andriy Halchenko, [[Konstantin Usov]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.golos.com.ua/Article.aspx?id=362038 |title=\u0421\u041f\u0418\u0421\u041e\u041a \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0456\u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438, \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0437\u0430\u0447\u0435\u0440\u0433\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0432\u0438\u0431\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0456\u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 26 \u0436\u043e\u0432\u0442\u043d\u044f 2014 \u0440\u043e\u043a\u0443 |publisher=\u00ab\u0413\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438\u00bb. \u2014 \u2116 218 (5968). \u2014 2014. \u2014 12 \u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430. \u2014 \u0421. 4\u20139 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141127122028/http://www.golos.com.ua/Article.aspx?id=362038 |archivedate=2014-11-27 }}</ref> In multimember districts city voted for [[Opposition Bloc]], union of all political forces that did not endorse [[Euromaidan]].\n\nIn the last decades, Kryvyi Rih has generally supported candidates belonging to the [[Party of Regions]] and (in the 1990s) [[Communist Party of Ukraine]] in national and local elections. Same situation was with presidential elections, strong support had [[Leonid Kuchma]] and [[Viktor Yanukovych]]. After 2014 events of [[Euromaidan]], mass demonstrations and clashes in central city,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.0564.ua/news/story/411 |title=\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d |publisher=0664 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129034418/http://www.0564.ua/news/story/411 |archive-date=2014-11-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Party of Regions|Regions]] lost its influence, and Kryvyi Rih supported [[Petro Poroshenko]].\n{{clear}}\n\n==Culture==\n[[File:\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0439-\u0420\u043e\u0433-\u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0430-\u0447\u0430\u0441\u044b-\u0446\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0435-\u0447\u0430\u0441\u044b-95804.jpeg|thumbnail|One of the biggest flower clocks in Europe is here; a local history museum is inside of it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://photo.ukrinform.ua/eng/current/photo.php?id=410459|title=World's biggest floral clock begins to tick off time in Ukraine's Kryvyi Rih|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>]]\nKryvyi Rih has a thriving theatre, circus and dance scene, and is home to a number of large performance venues. The first theater was the Coliseum, built in 1908. The New Theatre of Vyzenberh and Hrushevskyy followed in 1911, at the corner of Lenina and Kalynychenko streets. Kryvbas Theatre began its activities in 1931, and three years later was incorporated with the Shevchenko Theater. There are also the Doll Theatre and Movement Theatre.\n\nKryvyi Rih is noted as the birthplace [[Eugenie Gershoy]]. She emigrated to the United States with her family in 1903, and there became an American sculptor and watercolorist. Gershoy's work is in the collections of the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]], the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]], and the [[Smithsonian American Art Museum]]. Her papers are held at [[Syracuse University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://library.syr.edu/digital/guides/g/gershoy_e.htm|title=Eugenie Gershoy Papers: An inventory of her papers at Syracuse University|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref> Indie band [[Brunettes Shoot Blondes]], folk musician [[Eduard Drach]], actress [[Helena Makowska]], and dancer [[Vladimir Malakhov (dancer)|Vladimir Malakhov]] also originated in the city.\n\nThe first film screenings were conducted in the city in the early 1920s. In 1934 Lenin Cinema was built. Today there are three movie theaters: Olympus, [[Odessa Kino|Odessa]] and [[Multiplex Cinemas|Multiplex]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kinoafisha.ua/cinema/krivoj-rog/ |title=\u041a\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0448\u0430 |publisher=\u041a\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0448\u0430 |accessdate=}}</ref> The Kryvyi Rih Circus feature large-scale exhibition space where fairs are held.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kr-circus.info/ |title=Kryvyi Rih Circus |publisher=Kryvyi Rih Circus |accessdate=}}</ref> Soviet heritage are [[Palace of Culture|Palaces of Culture]] in every district of the city.\n\nThe local historical museum celebrates Cossack history, the industrial heritage of the area and its role in the Soviet State. The municipally owned Art Gallery houses a collection of local painting.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://1kr.ua/news-142.html |title=Local Museum |publisher=1KR UA |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nThe nightlife of the city has expanded significantly since the 2000s. Big clubs such as Hollywood<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vk.com/kr_hollywood |title=Hollywood city VK |publisher=Hollywood city VK |accessdate=}}</ref> and Sky, have attracted touring djs, pop and rap performers. Another major scene of the city is the Palace of Youth and Students of the [[Kryvyi Rih National University]] (KNU).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://knu.edu.ua/dozvillia-i-sport/palats-molodi-i-studentiv |title=KNU students Club |publisher=KNU |accessdate=}}</ref> The most popular fast-food, [[McDonald's]], is located at [[95th Block]].\n\n[[Ukrainian cuisine]] is found adjacent to a range of Jewish and popular American foods: [[bagel]]s, [[cheesecake]], [[hot dog]]s, [[shawarma]] and [[pizza]]. [[Japanese cuisine]] and other Asian restaurants, [[hookah]]s, [[sandwich]] joints, [[trattoria]]s and [[coffeehouse]]s have become ubiquitous. Other well-known places&nbsp;\u2013 City Pub and Prado Cafe. The city is home to the annual [[electronic music]] [[Turbofly]] festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vk.com/turbofly_kr |title=Turbofly VK |publisher=Turbofly VK |accessdate=}}</ref> [[Rock music|Rock]] band music, a tradition in the Ukraine, is an important part city's life and is hosted in few small pubs.\n{{clear}}\n\n==Landmarks==\nKryvyi Rih's buildings display a variety of architectural styles, ranging from [[eclecticism]] to [[contemporary architecture]]. The widespread use of red brick and block apartments characterize the city. Much of the architecture in the city was built during its prosperous days as a center for the ore trade. Just outside the immediate city center is a large number of former factories. Some have been totally destroyed; others are in desperate need of restoration.\n\n[[Stalinist architecture]] was the predominant style of postwar apartments, of 5 to 7 stories. City Hall is the best example of [[Stalinist architecture|The decree On liquidation of excesses]].<ref>''Architecture of The Stalin Era'', by Alexei Tarkhanov (Collaborator), Sergei Kavtaradze (Collaborator), Mikhail Anikst (Designer), 1992, {{ISBN|978-0-8478-1473-2}}</ref> [[Khrushchyovka]] is a type of low-cost, concrete-paneled or brick three- to five-storied apartment building which was developed in the USSR during the early 1960s. It was named after [[Nikita Khrushchev]], then premier of the Soviet government. Dozens of these aging buildings around the city are now past their design lifetime. There are six [[microdistrict]]s.\n\nThe city has many [[Ukrainian Orthodox Church (Moscow Patriarchate)|Christian churches]], the most notable being the Savior Transfiguration Cathedral of the Ukrainian Orthodox church. It is the base of the [[Kryvyi Rih Eparchy]], which was established on July 27, 1996.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eparhia.com.ua/?p=3|title=\u00bb \u0415\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0438\u044f|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref> Roman Catholic chapel located in old town. Pokrova church, Mykhailivska church and Christmas church were destroyed in the 1930s during the [[Great Purge]], never to be used as a church again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://1775.dp.ua/istoriya-ss/pravoslavnye-hramy|title=\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0445\u0440\u0430\u043c\u044b - \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0420\u043e\u0433\u0430 - 1775.dp.ua|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn Kryvyi Rih, the [[Judaism in Ukraine|Jewish community]] built a new, large synagogue, that opened in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jewish-museum-marmer.dp.ua/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2&Itemid=1|title=\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430|first=\u041f\u043e\u0434\u0434\u0443\u0431\u043d\u0430\u044f|last=\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u0430\u043d\u0430|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ru.tsn.ua/ukrayina/v-krivom-roge-otkryli-odnu-iz-krupneyshih-sinagog-v-vostochnoy-evrope.html|title=\u0412 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0420\u043e\u0433\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0434\u043d\u0443 \u0438\u0437 \u043a\u0440\u0443\u043f\u043d\u0435\u0439\u0448\u0438\u0445 \u0441\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0433 \u0432 \u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nLarge parks hold many of Kryvyi Rih's public monuments. There are numerous [[socialist realism]]-style monuments installed in the Soviet years to honor Cossacks, [[Olexander Paul]], [[Taras Shevchenko]] (2), [[Bohdan Khmelnytsky]] (3, since 1954), [[Vasili Marguelov]], [[Alexander Pushkin]], [[Fyodor Sergeyev]], [[Mikhail Lermontov]], and [[Maxim Gorky]]. The few [[Lenin]] monuments were destroyed during [[euromaidan]] events in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/759365|title=Vandals continue demolition of monuments to Vladimir Lenin in Ukraine|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref> Dozens of [[cenotaph]]s and memorials to [[Second World War]] soldiers were erected. A [[Sukhoi Su-15]] is on display near Aviator Club, [[Yakovlev Yak-40]] at [[National Aviation University]], Vyzvolennia Square hold [[IS tank family|IS3]] tank. [[Russian locomotive class Ye]] placed near [[Kryvyi Rih Main Station|Railway station]].\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nfile:\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0437\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0434 - \u042f\u043f\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432.JPG|Kryvyi Rih Botanical Gardens of [[National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine|NAS]]\nfile:\u041d\u043e\u0447\u044c\u044e \u0443 \u0422\u0435\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Shevchenko Theatre\nfile:\u0410\u0440\u0442-\u041c\u0430\u0439\u0434\u0430\u043d \u0443 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0442\u0435\u0430\u0442\u0440\u0430.jpg|Central Art Square\nfile:\u0417\u0438\u043c\u0430. \u0421\u043a\u0432\u0435\u0440 \u041f\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0438\u043d\u0430.jpg|Pushkin park in snow\n</gallery>\nKryvyi Rih has few<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kdpu.edu.ua/index.php?option=com_content&task=blogcategory&id=572&Itemid=826|title=\u041a\u0430\u0444\u0435\u0434\u0440\u0430 \u0456\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0457 \u043c\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438 - \u0422\u0435\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0445, \u043c\u0430\u0433\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0440\u043e\u0431\u0456\u0442|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref> designated [[natural monument]]s: the old [[pear]] near Karnavatka, another [[pear]] of 1789,<ref>\u0415\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0456\u044f \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0436\u0436\u044f. \u2014 \u0423 2-\u0445 \u0442./\u0423\u043f\u043e\u0440\u044f\u0434. \u0412. \u041f. \u0411\u0443\u0445\u0442\u0456\u044f\u0440\u043e\u0432. \u2014 \u041a\u0440. \u0420\u0456\u0433: \u00ab\u042f\u0412\u0412\u0410\u00bb, 2005</ref> Vizyrka landscape reserve, Northern and Southern Red Beam, Amphibolite, Arkose and Skelevatski Outputs, Mopr Rocks, Slate rocks, Sandstone rock.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libr.dp.ua/region/zapovedn.htm|title=\u041f\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0456 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438, \u0437\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0438, \u043f\u0430\u0440\u043a\u0438 \u0442\u0430 \u043f\u0430\u043c'\u044f\u0442\u043a\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0438 \u0414\u043d\u0456\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0457 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0456|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004232342/http://www.libr.dp.ua/region/zapovedn.htm|archive-date=4 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Park named after the newspaper [[Pravda]] is very famous by its [[Stalinist architecture|ampir]] boat station.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ru.foursquare.com/v/%D0%BF%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%BA-%D0%B8%D0%BC-%D0%B3%D0%B0%D0%B7%D0%B5%D1%82%D1%8B-%D0%BF%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B2%D0%B4%D0%B0/4f8a9cdbe4b0cec3ac4b2bda|title=\u041f\u0430\u0440\u043a \u0438\u043c. \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u044b \"\u041f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430\"|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref> Kryvyi Rih Botanical Gardens of the [[National Academy of Sciences of Ukraine]] (NAS) was established in 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://garden.gov.ua/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=64&Itemid=180|title=\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0456\u0437\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0431\u043e\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0434 \u041d\u0410\u041d \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Kryvyi Rih National University.JPG|thumb|[[Kryvyi Rih National University]]]]\nMajor [[Kryvyi Rih National University]] was originally formed as college and Mining Institute in 1929.  It gained university status in 1982. [[Kryvyi Rih Pedagogical Institute]] it was founded in 1930 as an Institute of Vocational Training, is the oldest pedagogical institution in Kryvyi Rih, reorganized in Pedagogical Institute. In 2011 Cabinet of Ukraine founded Kryvyi Rih National University by uniting Mining Institute, Pedagogical University, Economic Institute of [[Kyiv National Economic University]] and Department of the [[National Metallurgical Academy of Ukraine]].\n\nOther institutions are local Department of Dnepropetrovsk State University of Internal Affairs, campuses of [[Zaporizhzhya National University]], [[National University Odesa Law Academy]] and [[Interregional Academy of Personnel Management]], college of [[National Aviation University]].\n\nIn 2014 Donetsk Tugan-Baranovsky National University of Economics and Trade was evacuated to Kryvyi Rih after a long [[War in Donbass]]. Its future is uncertain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://zn.ua/UKRAINE/iz-doneckoy-i-luganskoy-oblastey-evakuirovany-uzhe-devyat-universitetov-157730_.html|title=\u0418\u0437 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0438 \u041b\u0443\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439 \u044d\u0432\u0430\u043a\u0443\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044b \u0443\u0436\u0435 \u0434\u0435\u0432\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0432 |publisher=ZN UA |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Frances Cairncross]] (in April 2010) \"There are too many small universities, the majority of which are ineffectively governed and mired in [[Corruption in Ukraine#Corruption in higher education|corruption]]. They are not able to withstand existing global challenges.\"<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/education-problems-deeper-than-language-63027.html Education problems deeper than language], [[Kyiv Post]] (2 April 2010)</ref> According to [[Anders \u00c5slund]] (in October 2012) the quality of doctoral education is bad, particularly in management training, economics, law and languages.<ref name=AAonUESO12>[http://www.kyivpost.com/opinion/op-ed/why-ukraine-keeps-falling-behind-educationally-economically-313833.html Outdated educational system translates into lagging economy], [[Kyiv Post]] (4 October 2012)</ref> He also signaled that the greatest problem in the Ukrainian education system is corruption.<ref name=AAonUESO12/>\n\nThere are 149 general secondary schools and 150 nursery schools and kindergartens in Kryvyi Rih.<ref name=\"Kryvyi Rih City Council\">{{cite web |url = http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/ua/osxfile/pg/70714144642580_n_1o/965668065.pdf |title = \u0411\u044e\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0435\u043d\u044c \"\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433 \u0443 \u0446\u0438\u0444\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u0456 \u0444\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0430\u0445 2013 \u0440. |year = 2013 |format = PDF |publisher = Kryvyi Rih City Council |access-date = 2014-11-20 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141129034856/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/ua/osxfile/pg/70714144642580_n_1o/965668065.pdf |archive-date = 2014-11-29 |url-status = dead }}</ref> Additionally, there are evening schools for adults, musical, art, sports and specialist technical schools.\n\n==Sport==\n[[File:Kryvyi Rih Metalurh Stadium 3.jpg|thumb|[[Metalurh Stadium (Kryvyi Rih)|Metalurh Stadium]], home ground of [[FC Kryvbas Kryvyi Rih]]]]\n\n[[FC Hirnyk Kryvyi Rih]] is a [[Association football|football]] club based in Hirnyk Stadium, and currently competes in the [[Ukrainian First League]]. It is part of the Sports Club Hirnyk which combines several other sections. The club's owner is the Kryvyi Rih Iron Ore Combine (KZRK), the biggest subterranean mining public company in Ukraine.\n\nKryvyi Rih was also home to another football team, [[FC Kryvbas Kryvyi Rih|Kryvbas Kryvyi Rih]]. The team was founded as FC Kryvyi Rih in 1959. The next year it was part of the republican sports society Avanhard. After a couple of years, it changed to Hirnyk, before obtaining current its name in 1966. Kryvbas debuted in the [[Ukrainian Premier League]] in the [[1992\u201393 Vyshcha Liha|1992\u201393 season]]. They had been in the top league since their debut, with their best finish in third place in the 1998\u201399 and 1999\u20132000 seasons. At the end of the  [[2012\u201313 Ukrainian Premier League|2012\u201313 season]] the team finished in 7th place, however, due to financial difficulties the club declared itself bankrupt in June 2013.\n[[FC Kryvbas-2 Kryvyi Rih]] was the reserve team of Kryvbas. In 1998 the club entered into the professional leagues to compete in the [[Ukrainian Second League|Second League]]. In 3 seasons the club moved to the Amateur Level before competing one last time in [[Ukrainian Second League|Second League]].\n\n[[SC Kryvbas]] is a professional basketball club. Achievements of the team are winning the Ukrainian Basketball League in 2009 and winning the Higher League in 2003 and 2004. Since 2010 the team is active in the [[Ukrainian Basketball SuperLeague]].\n\nThe city is famous for its annual autorally. It was also the birthplace of the Ukrainian tennis players [[Valeria Bondarenko]], [[Alona Bondarenko]] and [[Kateryna Bondarenko]].\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:\u0421\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044b \u041c\u041e\u041f\u0420\u0430.jpg|thumb|Mopr rocks]]\n[[File:Kryvyi rih roads and signs.jpg|thumbnail|Red-colored ground is common because of the [[iron oxide]]s.]]\nAt {{Coord|47|55|0|N|33|15|0|E|type:city}}, {{convert|415|km|mi|sigfig=2}} south of [[Kiev]], the city extends for 126&nbsp;km from north to south,<ref>''Dnepropetrovsk Oblast'' 1:200,000 map, Ukraine 2004 and 2005.</ref><ref>The following website claims that: \"Currently, the city of Krivoy Rog has an area of {{cvt|430.0|km2}}, and extends {{convert|126|km|2|abbr=on}} from north to south (the largest in Europe) and is {{convert|20|km|2|abbr=on}} in width.\" (\"\u0412 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043e\u044f\u0449\u0438\u0439 \u043c\u043e\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0433 \u0437\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043c\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044e \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u044c\u044e 430,0 \u043a\u043c2 \u0438 \u0438\u043c\u0435\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u044f\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0441 \u0441\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u044e\u0433 126 \u043a\u043c (\u043d\u0430\u0438\u0431\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0432 \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435) \u0438 \u0448\u0438\u0440\u0438\u043d\u0443 \u0434\u043e 20 \u043a\u043c.:) [http://www.kryvyirih.dp.ua/ru/st/pg/171109377267456_s/ \u041e\u0444\u0438\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0441\u0430\u0439\u0442 \u0438\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0441\u043e\u043c\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0449\u0433\u0449 \u0420\u043e\u0433\u043e] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110425103906/http://www.kryvyirih.dp.ua/ru/st/pg/171109377267456_s/ |date=2011-04-25 }} (ru) [http://www.kryvyirih.dp.ua/ua/st/pg/171109377267456_s/ (ua)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110319212050/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/ua/st/pg/171109377267456_s/ |date=2011-03-19 }}.</ref> paralleling the [[ore]] [[deposition (geology)|deposit]]s. The city centre is on the east bank of the [[Inhulets River]], near its confluences with the River [[Saksahan]]. Kryvyi Rih's geographic features were highly influential in its early development industrial city.\n\nThe city is set in the rolling steppe land surrounded by fields of sunflowers and grain. A short distance east of the city center, there is an area along a small lake where glacial boulders were deposited. As a result, this area was never cultivated and contains one of the few remaining patches of wild [[steppe]] vegetation in the area. The city's [[natural environment|environmental]] and [[construction]] [[safety]] is a growing problem due to abandoned [[Mining|mines]] and [[pollution|polluted]] ore-processing [[waste]]. According to the Scientific Hygienic Centre of Ukraine, the city is one of the most unfavorable places to live because of these problems.<ref name=environment>[http://www.lib.ua-ru.net/inode/25488.html \u0411\u0438\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043e\u0442\u0435\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u0430\u0432\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0444\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b], Scientific Hygienic Centre of Ukraine.</ref>\n\n===Climate===\nKryvyi Rih experiences a dry warm [[Humid continental climate|continental climate]] (''Dfa'') according to the K\u00f6ppen climate classification system, like much of southern Ukraine. This tends to generate warm summers and cold winters with relatively low precipitation. Snowfalls are not common in the city, due to the urban warming effect. However,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.0564.ua/news/110563|title=\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0433 \u0432\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0442\u0438\u043b \u0441\u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0434 \u0432\u043e \u0432\u0441\u0435\u043e\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u0438?|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref> districts that surround the city receive more snow and roads leading out of the city can be closed<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nbnews.com.ua/ru/news/111848/|title=\u041d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0435 \u0431\u044e\u0440\u043e \u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439 - \u0418\u0437-\u0437\u0430 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u0437\u0430\u0431\u043b\u043e\u043a\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e \u0434\u0432\u0438\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0447\u0435\u0442\u044b\u0440\u0435\u0445 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044f\u0445 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b|first=\u041d\u0435\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0438\u0441\u0438\u043c\u043e\u0435 \u0431\u044e\u0440\u043e|last=\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171229112224/http://nbnews.com.ua/ru/news/111848/|archive-date=29 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> due to snow.\n{{Weather box\n| location = Kryvyi Rih\n| metric first = Yes\n| single line  = Yes\n| width = auto\n| Jan record high C = 15.0\n| Feb record high C = 18.9\n| Mar record high C = 23.5\n| Apr record high C = 31.8\n| May record high C = 35.8\n| Jun record high C = 36.4\n| Jul record high C = 38.6\n| Aug record high C = 39.6\n| Sep record high C = 36.4\n| Oct record high C = 31.7\n| Nov record high C = 21.7\n| Dec record high C = 15.3\n| year record high C = 39.6\n| Jan high C = -0.7\n| Feb high C = 0.3\n| Mar high C = 5.9\n| Apr high C = 15.1\n| May high C = 21.8\n| Jun high C = 25.3\n| Jul high C = 27.9\n| Aug high C = 27.6\n| Sep high C = 21.5\n| Oct high C = 14.1\n| Nov high C = 5.5\n| Dec high C = 0.6\n| year high C = 13.7\n| Jan mean C = -3.5\n| Feb mean C = -3.1\n| Mar mean C = 1.9\n| Apr mean C = 9.6\n| May mean C = 15.9\n| Jun mean C = 19.5\n| Jul mean C = 21.8\n| Aug mean C = 21.2\n| Sep mean C = 15.6\n| Oct mean C = 9.1\n| Nov mean C = 2.3\n| Dec mean C = -2.1\n| year mean C = 9.0\n| Jan low C = -6.1\n| Feb low C = -6.0\n| Mar low C = -1.8\n| Apr low C = 4.5\n| May low C = 10.0\n| Jun low C = 13.9\n| Jul low C = 15.9\n| Aug low C = 15.2\n| Sep low C = 10.3\n| Oct low C = 4.9\n| Nov low C = -0.6\n| Dec low C = -4.6\n| year low C = 4.6\n| Jan record low C = -31.1\n| Feb record low C = -27.3\n| Mar record low C = -21.0\n| Apr record low C = -8.9\n| May record low C = -2.6\n| Jun record low C = 2.8\n| Jul record low C = 7.3\n| Aug record low C = 2.8\n| Sep record low C = -3.7\n| Oct record low C = -10.0\n| Nov record low C = -18.1\n| Dec 