Moldovans in Ukraine|Moldovan]]\n|-\n|[[Poles in Ukraine|Polish]]\n|-\n|[[Jews in Ukraine|Jewish]]\n|-\n|[[Romani people in Ukraine|Romani]]\n|-\n|[[Georgians|Georgian]]\n|}\n{| class=\"infobox\"\n|<timeline>\nColors= \n  id:lightgrey value:gray(0.9)\n  id:darkgrey  value:gray(0.7)\n  id:canvas value:rgb(1,1,1)\n  id:barra value:rgb(0.6,0.7,0.8)\nImageSize = width:auto height:220 barincrement:30\nPlotArea = left:60 bottom:50 top:20 right:20\nDateFormat = yyyy\nPeriod = from:0 till:800000\nTimeAxis = orientation:vertical\nAlignBars = late\nBackgroundColors = canvas:canvas\nScaleMajor = gridcolor:darkgrey increment:100000 start:0\nScaleMinor = gridcolor:lightgrey increment:100000 start:0\nBarData= \n  bar:1781 text:1781\n  bar:1859 text:1859\n  bar:1887 text:1887\n  bar:1896 text:1896\n  bar:1916 text:1916\n  bar:1920 text:1920\n  bar:1923 text:1923\n  bar:1939 text:1939\n  bar:1941 text:1941\n  bar:1956 text:1956\n  bar:1969 text:1969\n  bar:1989 text:1989\n  bar:2001 text:2001\n  bar:2009 text:2009\n  bar:2014 text:2014\nPlotData= \n  color:barra width:5 align:left\n  bar:1781 from:0 till:2184\n  bar:1859 from:0 till:3644\n  bar:1887 from:0 till:6000\n  bar:1896 from:0 till:17000\n  bar:1916 from:0 till:26700\n  bar:1920 from:0 till:22700\n  bar:1923 from:0 till:19000\n  bar:1939 from:0 till:197000\n  bar:1941 from:0 till:213000\n  bar:1956 from:0 till:322000\n  bar:1969 from:0 till:623000\n  bar:1989 from:0 till:769100\n  bar:2001 from:0 till:712500\n  bar:2009 from:0 till:674866\n  bar:2014 from:0 till:654900\nTextData= \n  fontsize: S pos:(180,30)\n  text: Kryvyi Rih Population\n</timeline>\n|}\nHistorically the population of Kryvyi Rih began to increase rapidly during the [[Interwar period]], peaking at 197 000 in 1939.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite web |url = http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/ua/osxfile/name/10813377938441_s_1o/ |title = \u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043d\u043e\u0437 \u043c\u0456\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0420\u043e\u0433\u0443. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433 |year = 2013 |format = PDF |publisher = Kryvyi Rih City Council |access-date = 2014-11-20 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141129034542/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/ua/osxfile/name/10813377938441_s_1o/ |archive-date = 2014-11-29 |url-status = dead }}</ref> From then the population began to decrease rapidly. Foreign workers arrived, and there was increased building of social housing estates by the Kryvyi Rih City Council after the Second World War, such as Sotshorod and Sonyachny.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok |title=\u0406\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0445\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0456\u043a\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0456\u0439 (\u043c. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433) |publisher=kryvyirih.dp.ua |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102000941/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/istorichniy_rozvitok |archive-date=2014-11-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe 2014 estimate for the population of Kryvyi Rih was 654,900 (8th in Ukraine). This was a decrease of 4 348 since the 2013 estimate. Since 2001, the population has grown by 48 001. In 2013, deaths exceeded births by 3589.\n[[Net migration rate]] is 234 (negative).<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/zagalna_informatsiya/demografichna_situatsiya|title=\u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u0441\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0430\u0446i\u044f|publisher=Kryvyi Rih City Council|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141102004146/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/pro_misto_kriviy_rig/zagalna_informatsiya/demografichna_situatsiya|archive-date=2014-11-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[UNHCR]] and City Council, 7000 people of [[Donetsk]] and [[Luhansk]] have fled to Kryvyi Rih since the beginning of 2014 [[War in Donbass]], not including those who did not register as asylum seekers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/world/europe/more-than-a-million-ukrainians-have-been-displaced-un-says.html |title=More Than a Million Ukrainians Have Been Displaced, U.N. Says |publisher=The New York Times |date=2 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.de/%D0%BE%D0%BE%D0%BD-%D0%B4%D0%BE%D0%BC%D1%96%D0%B2%D0%BA%D0%B8-%D1%87%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B7-%D0%B1%D0%BE%D0%B9%D0%BE%D0%B2%D1%96-%D0%B4%D1%96%D1%97-%D0%B2-%D1%83%D0%BA%D1%80%D0%B0%D1%97%D0%BD%D1%96-%D0%BF%D0%BE%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%88%D0%B8%D0%BB%D0%B8-%D0%BF%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B0%D0%B4-415-%D1%82%D0%B8%D1%81%D1%8F%D1%87-%D0%BB%D1%8E%D0%B4%D0%B5%D0%B9/a-17868525 |title=\u041e\u041e\u041d: \u0414\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0432\u043a\u0438 \u0447\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0437 \u0431\u043e\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0456 \u0434\u0456\u0457 \u0432 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0456 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0448\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0434 415 \u0442\u0438\u0441\u044f\u0447 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439 |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=August 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.de/unhcr-730000-flee-ukraine-for-russia/a-17833179 |title=UNHCR: 730,000 flee Ukraine for Russia |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=August 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://krlife.com.ua/news/v-krivoi-rog-opyat-massovo-kinulis-bezhentsy-s-vostoka |title=\u0412 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0433 \u043e\u043f\u044f\u0442\u044c \u043c\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043e\u0432\u043e \u043a\u0438\u043d\u0443\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u0431\u0435\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0441 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0430 |publisher=krlife.com.ua}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://krlife.com.ua/tags/tegi/bezhentsy |title=\u041d\u0430 \u0414\u043d\u0456\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0456 \u0431\u0443\u0434\u0443\u0442\u044c \u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0456 \u0431\u0456\u0437\u043d\u0435\u0441-\u0446\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0438 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0456\u0432 |publisher=krlife.com.ua}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://dnepr.comments.ua/news/2014/09/18/093736.html |title=\u0421\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0446\u0435\u0432 \u0441 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439 \u0432 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0420\u043e\u0433\u0435? |publisher=comments.ua |access-date=2014-11-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319062245/http://dnepr.comments.ua/news/2014/09/18/093736.html |archive-date=2015-03-19 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nKryvyi Rih historically had a Christian majority-population.  It has numerous churches, particularly in the central city. The well-known Savior Transfiguration Cathedral in Saksahan Raion is [[Ukrainian Orthodox Church (Moscow Patriarchate)|Orthodox]] administrative center, bishop of the [[Kryvyi Rih Eparchy]] has his main residence here. The town has a school of [[icon painting]]. The patron saint of the city is [[Saint Nicholas]], as well as bishops Onufry and Porphyry.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://most-dnepr.info/photo-report/photo-society/v_krivom_roge_aleksandr_vilkul_otkryl_pamjatnik_pokroviteljam_goroda_svjatym_onufriju_i_porfiriju.htm |title=\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0414\u043d\u0435\u043f\u0440 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129054022/http://most-dnepr.info/photo-report/photo-society/v_krivom_roge_aleksandr_vilkul_otkryl_pamjatnik_pokroviteljam_goroda_svjatym_onufriju_i_porfiriju.htm |archive-date=2014-11-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThis was long a centre of Jewish population. Its Central Synagogue was the tallest building in town in the late 19th century. The majority of region's Jews live here, and a significant Jewish community has been re-established. Beis Shtern Shtulman Synagogue<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.krjew.com/|title=\u0415\u0432\u0440\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0420\u043e\u0433\u0430|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801222634/http://krjew.com/|archive-date=1 August 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> opened in 2010 in the Central City. In the early twentieth century, the city had two synagogues, located on Kaunas street. As part of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Kharkiv-Zaporizhia]], the city has the Kostel of Mary Mother of Jesus. Kryvyi Rih is also home to Evangelical Christians, CEF, and [[Vedas]] communities.\n\nIn terms of ethnic composition, there are no official statistics. Jews have made up the single largest [[ethnic minority]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/obednannya_gromadyan|title=\u041c\u0456\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u043e\u0441\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043a\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0434\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u043e\u0440\u0433\u0430\u043d\u0456\u0437\u0430\u0446\u0456\u0439 \u0442\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u2019\u0454\u0434\u043d\u0430\u043d\u044c|publisher=kryvyirih.dp.ua|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927233352/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/obednannya_gromadyan|archive-date=2015-09-27|url-status=dead}}</ref> Today they number 15 000, followed by [[Russians]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2010}}, and [[Armenians]].\n\nLarge immigrant groups include people from [[Korea]], [[Poland]], [[Moldova]], [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] and [[Azerbaijan]], and [[Romani people|Roms]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cityblog.com.ua/2013/09/festival-natsionalno-kulturnyih-soobshhestv-v-krivom-roge/|title=\u0424\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e-\u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432 \u0432 \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0420\u043e\u0433\u0435.|date=23 September 2013|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170111002639/http://cityblog.com.ua/2013/09/festival-natsionalno-kulturnyih-soobshhestv-v-krivom-roge/|archive-date=11 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Numerous [[African people|African]] students come to the city to attend local universities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://doir.knu.edu.ua/%D0%BC%D1%96%D0%B6%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BD%D0%B0-%D0%B4%D1%96%D1%8F%D0%BB%D1%8C%D0%BD%D1%96%D1%81%D1%82%D1%8C/%D0%BF%D0%B0%D1%80%D1%82%D0%BD%D0%B5%D1%80%D0%B8-%D1%83%D0%BD%D1%96%D0%B2%D0%B5%D1%80%D1%81%D0%B8%D1%82%D0%B5%D1%82%D1%83/ |title=KNU International|publisher=KNU |accessdate=}}</ref> Central city and Dovhuntsevskyi Raion are centres of population for ethnic minorities.\n\nThe [[Kryvyi Rih Metropolitan Region]] has a population of 1 010 000 in 2010. In addition to Kryvyi Rih, the KMR includes the five raions of the [[Dnipropetrovsk Oblast]]. The KMR is the sixth-largest within Ukraine.\n{{clear right}}\n\n==Economy==\n\nIn mid-2014 Kryvyi Rih had a [[Industrial production index|IPI]] of \u20b441.6bn<ref name=\"Kryvyi Rih City Council\"/><ref name=\"\u0415\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043d\u043e\u0437. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433\">{{cite web |url = http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/ua/osxfile/pg/171109856079101_s_11o |title = \u0415\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043d\u043e\u0437. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433 |year = 2013 |format = PDF |publisher = Kryvyi Rih City Council |access-date = 2014-11-20 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141129034849/http://kryvyirih.dp.ua/ua/osxfile/pg/171109856079101_s_11o |archive-date = 2014-11-29 |url-status = dead }}</ref> (about $3bn<ref name=\"xe.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.xe.com/currencycharts/?from=UAH&to=USD|title=XE: UAH / USD Currency Chart. Ukrainian Hryvnia to US Dollar Rates|publisher=|accessdate=10 January 2017}}</ref>) with 17.9% growth which is 41.8% of [[Dnipropetrovsk Oblast]] IPI. Export reached $2.520m (4.9% decrease), Import - $276m. City got $4.899m of foreign [[Investment]]ments, mainly from [[Germany]], [[Cyprus]], [[Netherlands]], and the [[UK]].\n\nOfficial unemployment throughout 2014 averaged 0.63%. [[Average wage]] is \u20b44.022 ($266,<ref name=\"xe.com\"/> 19.4% more than average Ukraine).<ref name=\"Kryvyi Rih City Council\"/><ref name=\"\u0415\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043d\u043e\u0437. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433\"/>\n\nProcessing and [[mining industry]] - the two largest sectors of Kryvyi Rih. Rest fraction is about 50%.  City has over 53<ref>{{cite web|url=http://info.1kr.ua/category-423-482.html?private_property=-1&p=5 |title=\u041f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u044b\u0448\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e-\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043f\u0440\u0438\u044f\u0442\u0438\u044f - \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0433 |accessdate=10 January 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170108185918/http://info.1kr.ua/category-423-482.html?private_property=-1&p=5 |archivedate=8 January 2017 }}</ref> plants, mines and factories. [[ArcelorMittal Kryvyi Rih]], owned by [[ArcelorMittal]] since 2005 is the largest private company by revenue in Ukraine,<ref>[http://www.kyivpost.com/media/images/data/images/01-32_KyivPost_38-9/original.jpg Top Ukrainian Companies By Revenue]</ref> producing over 7 million tonnes of crude steel, and mined over 17 million tonnes of iron ore. As of 2011, the company employed about 37 000 people. 4 Iron Ore Enrichment Works of [[Metinvest]] are a large contributors to the UA's [[balance of payments]]. Another giants of city are [[Evraz]] mining company and [[HeidelbergCement]].<ref name=\"Kryvyi Rih City Council\"/><ref name=\"\u0415\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043d\u043e\u0437. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433\"/>\n\n==Transport==\nLocal public transportation in Kryvyi Rih includes the [[Kryvyi Rih Metrotram|Metrotram]] (underground), [[bus]]es<ref name=\"Kryvyi Rih City Council\"/><ref name=\"\u0415\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043d\u043e\u0437. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433\"/> and [[marshrutka|minibuses]] line, [[Trolleybuses in Kryvyi Rih|trolleybuses]] (in operation since 1957, the system presently comprises 23 routes), [[Kryvyi Rih Tramway|trams]] (one of the world's largest tram networks, operating on 105.8 kilometres of total route. As of 2014, it was composed of 13 lines) and, [[taxi]].\n\nThe publicly owned and operated Kryvyi Rih Metrotram is the fastest, the most convenient and affordable network that covers most, but not all, of the city. The Metrotram is continuously expanding towards the city limits to meet growing demand, currently has three lines with a total length of {{convert|18.7|km|abbr=off}} and 11 stations. Despite its designation as a \"[[Metro (rapid transit)|metro]] [[tram]]\" and its use of [[tram car]]s as rolling stock, the Kryvyi Rih Metrotram is a complete [[rapid transit system]] with enclosed stations and tracks separated both from roads and from the city's conventional tram lines.\nCity public transport serviced 66m persons in the first part of 2014.<ref name=\"Kryvyi Rih City Council\"/><ref name=\"\u0415\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0456\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043d\u043e\u0437. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u0420\u0456\u0433\"/>\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nfile:KRMetrotram.jpg|[[Kryvyi Rih Metrotram]] at [[Zarichna (Kryvyi Rih Metrotram)|Zarichna station]]\nFile:Kryvyi Rih - Prospekt Metalurhiv.jpg|Prospekt Metalurhiv station of the Kryvyi Rih Metrotram was Opened in 1989\nfile:LAZ trolleybus at the station Krivoy Rog-Chief.jpg|[[Trolleybuses in Kryvyi Rih]]\nfile:Electric train at station Krivoy Rog-Chief.jpg|[[Commuter rail]] train at the [[Kryvyi Rih Main Station]]. The city's railroads have a long history.\n</gallery>\n\nThe Kryvyi Rih public transport system, except for taxi, uses a simple [[flat rate]] tariff system regardless of distance traveled: tickets or tokens must be purchased each time a vehicle is boarded. Discount passes are available for grade school and higher education students. Pensioners use public transportation free. Ticket prices are regulated by the city government, and the cost of one ride is far lower than in Western Europe.\n\nThe historic [[Kryvyi Rih Tramway|tram system]],<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> once a well maintained and widely used method of transport, is now gradually being phased out in favor of buses and trolleybuses.\n\nThe city has no cycling lines. The [[Taxicab|taxi]] market is expansive but not regulated. In particular, the taxi fare per kilometer is not regulated. There is a fierce competition between private taxi companies.\n\n[[Kryvyi Rih International Airport]] is the airport that serves the city. It is located 17.5&nbsp;km (10.9 Miles) northwest of the city of Kryvyi Rih.\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n{{see also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Ukraine}}\nKryvyi Rih is [[Sister city|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=\u041c\u0456\u0436\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043f\u0456\u0432\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0446\u044f|url=https://kr.gov.ua/investitsiyne_seredovishche/propozitsii_inozemnikh_partneriv|website=kr.gov.ua|publisher=Kryvyi Rih|language=uk|accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|BLR}} [[Zhodzina]] , Belarus\n\n===Friendly cities===\n*{{flagicon|SVK}} [[Ko\u0161ice]], Slovakia\n*{{flagicon|POL}} [[Lublin]], Poland\n*{{flagicon|HUN}} [[Miskolc]], Hungary\n\n==See also==\n*[[:Category:People from Kryvyi Rih|List of people from Kryvyi Rih]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=nb}}\n==References==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n* ''\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0436\u044c\u0435. \u0421\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u043a-\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b''\u044c / \u0414\u043d\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a: \u0414\u043d\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u043a\u043d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e, 1963. \u2014 162 \u0441. (in Russian)\n* ''\u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0420\u043e\u0433\u0443 \u2014 200. \u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043e-\u044d\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a'' / \u0420\u0435\u0434\u043a\u043e\u043b\u043b\u0435\u0433\u0438\u044f: \u041f. \u041b. \u0412\u0430\u0440\u0433\u0430\u0442\u044e\u043a \u0438 \u0434\u0440. \u2014 \u0414\u043d\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a: \u00ab\u041f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0456\u043d\u044c\u00bb, 1975. \u2014 208 \u0441. (in Russian)\n* \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043a \u041b. \u0418. \u041a\u0440\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0433: ''\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c-\u0441\u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438''\u043a / \u041b. \u0418. \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043a, \u0414. \u0418. \u041a\u0430\u043d. \u2014 \u0414\u043d\u0435\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a: \u00ab\u041f\u0440\u043e\u043ci\u043d\u044c\u00bb, 1986. \u2014 191 \u0441., \u0446\u0432. \u0438\u043b. (in Russian)\n* \u041f\u0430\u0445\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0432 \u0410. \u0413., ''\u0411\u043e\u0